    <bioghist>
      <head>Historical Note</head>
      <p>On February 22, 1869 Rev. J. W. Wellman, D.D brought the idea of the Congregational Club to
        a Pastor's Meeting in Boston, Massachusetts. The club was fully established, with a
        constitution and officers, by April 20th of the same year. The goal of the club was to
        "energize Congregationalism" by encouraging cameraderie and cooperation among
        Congregationalists, particularly in the Boston area. The club fostered this community with
        monthly discussions, and formal social gatherings such as their Annual Festival and
        Forefathers' Day.</p>
      <p>This collection contains records through 1947, but the club continued to exist until it was
        disbanded at some point between 1978 and 1981.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent>
      <head>Scope and Contents</head>
      <p>This collection contains records documenting the activity of the Congregational Club from
        its inception in 1869 to 1961. It contains records relating to administration, events held
        by the club, and necrologies.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement>
      <head>Arrangement</head>
      <p>The Congregational Club records have been arranged into the three series listed below.
        Within each series materials have been primarily arranged in chronological order by start
        date. When appropriate, similar and continuous materials have been grouped together.</p>
      <p><emph render="italic">Series 1:</emph> Administration, 1869-1961</p>
      <p><emph render="italic">Series 2:</emph> Necrologies, 1870-1916</p>
      <p><emph render="italic">Series 3:</emph> Events, 1871-1944</p>
    </arrangement>
    <relatedmaterial>
      <head>Related Materials</head>
      <p>Additional records related to the Congregational Club can be found in the Roslindale,
        Boston, Mass. Highland Congregational Church records, 1869-2006, RG4824.</p>
    </relatedmaterial>
